## The story so far

The current situation surrounding Warner Bros. Discovery did not begin with a hostile bid or a contested tender offer. It began years earlier with a strategic reassessment inside AT&T about the role of media assets on a telecommunications balance sheet. That reassessment set in motion a transaction that reshaped ownership, governance, and capital structure, and created the company now at the center of competing strategic interest from Netflix and Paramount.

Understanding how Warner Bros. Discovery was formed is essential to understanding the constraints and options facing the board today.

## Verified facts

- On May 17, 2021, AT&T announced a transaction to separate WarnerMedia and combine it with Discovery.
- The transaction was structured as a Reverse Morris Trust–style separation, resulting in a new publicly traded media company.
- The transaction closed on April 11, 2022, at which point Warner Bros. Discovery began trading as a combined entity.
- AT&T shareholders received shares in Warner Bros. Discovery as part of the separation, while Discovery shareholders retained ownership in the combined company.
- At inception, Warner Bros. Discovery assumed a substantial debt load as part of the transaction structure.

